05530nam a22007815i 9780773597402DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735974027 a10.1515/97807735974022doi  a(DE-B1597)656079  a(OCoLC)908308805  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aR727.3 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a610.9409/0332231 aBoon, Sonja, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTelling the Flesh :bLife Writing, Citizenship, and the Body in the Letters to Samuel Auguste Tissot /cSonja Boon. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (360 p.) :b4 photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's/Associated Medical Services Studies in the History of Medicine, Health, and Society ;v4400tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tBodies and Stories -- tBody Logics: Letters and Lives -- tTextual Bodies/Textual Selves: Illness, Identity, and Bodily Subjectivity -- tCorporeal Virtue and Embodied Citizenship -- tConstitutionally Autobiographical: Performing Kinship -- tBodily Agency and the Politics of Pleasure -- tNeurographia: Writing Nervous Disorder -- tAs long as we -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn the second half of the eighteenth century, celebrated Swiss physician Samuel Auguste Tissot (1728-1797) received over 1,200 medical consultation letters from across Europe and beyond. Written by individuals seeking respite from a range of ailments, these letters offer valuable insight into the nature of physical suffering. Plaintive, desperate, querulous, fearful, frustrated, and sometimes arrogant and self-interested in tone, the letters to Tissot not only express the struggle of individuals to understand the body and its workings, but also reveal the close connections between embodiment and politics. Through the process of writing letters to describe their ailments, the correspondents created textual versions of themselves, articulating identities shaped by their physical experiences. Using these identities and experiences as examples, Sonja Boon argues that the complaints voiced in the letters were intimately linked to broader social and political discourses of citizenship in the late eighteenth century, a period beset with concerns about depopulation, moral depravity, and corporeal excess, and organized around intricate rules of propriety. Contributing to the fields of literary criticism, history, gender and sexuality studies, and history of medicine, Telling the Flesh establishes a compelling argument about the connections between health, politics, and identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCitizenshipxPolitical aspectsxHistoryx18th centuryxEurope. 0aCitizenshipxPolitical aspectszEuropexHistoryy18th century. 0aCorps humain dans la littérature. 0aCorps humainxAspect socialxHistoirex18e sièclexEurope. 0aEuropean lettersy18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aHuman bodyxPoliticals aspectsxHistoryx18th centuryxEurope. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectsxHistoryx18th centuryxEurope. 0aHuman bodyxSocial aspectszEuropexHistoryy18th century. 0aHuman bodyzEuropexPoliticals aspectsxHistoryy18th century. 0aLettres européennes (Genre littéraire)xHistoire et critiquex18e siècle. 0aMaladesxCorrespondancexEurope. 0aMedicinexHistoryx18th centuryxEurope. 0aMedicinexHistoryy18th century. 0aMedicinezEuropexHistoryy18th century. 0aPatients' writingsxHistory and criticism. 0aPhysician and patientxHistoryx18th centuryxEurope. 0aPhysician and patientzEuropexHistoryy18t